  "text": "Among hundreds of reports using PCR, except for the urine study, 81 none established their role for diagnosis. Inadequate numbers of patients were studied, insufficient numbers of individual specimen types (BAL, sputum, body fluids, tissue) were tested, and validation was inadequate to establish precision and reproducibility. Also, FDA cleared devices are unavailable. The only established role for molecular methods is DovePress identification of organisms isolated from culture. [CITATION_1] A meta-analysis evaluating results from five studies in Latin America reported sensitivity of 95.4% and specificity of 98.7% but concluded that the available studies were inadequate to recommend PCR. [CITATION_2] In 2017, the WHO recognized histoplasmosis as a significant opportunistic infection and a major cause of death in patients with advanced HIV disease, especially in the hyperendemic areas. In 2019, the WHO included Histoplasma antigen tests on the second edition of the EDL (Lists of Essential In Vitro Diagnostics).",
